observations.recommendation:
The Local Chief Executive, as the GFPS Chairperson, ensure that at least 5% of the total annual budget is set aside for activities that support GAD plans and programs;

The Accounting Office install Responsibility Centers for their GFPS to facilitate the generation of all reports pertaining to GAD-related expenses and other GAD-related financial transactions, and to monitor and properly account for the GAD funds;

The Budget Office to monitor the utilization of the 5% GAD fund based on the DILG-endorsed GAD Plan and Budget of the LGU; and

The GAD Focal Person coordinate with the Accounting Office and the Budget Office in the preparation of the GAD Accomplishment Report.

Require the Accounting Unit to practice the imposition of liquidated damages to defaulting suppliers to encourage prompt deliveries of goods to the Municipality and to ensure that all documentary requirements are all in order before processing the disbursement vouchers;

Require the Procuring Office personnel to ensure that all details of the Purchase Orders are provided for proper accountability and transparency;

Require the Supply Officer or authorized personnel to accomplish the Inspection and Acceptance Reports (IARs) completely and properly;

Require the Supply Officer or authorized personnel to ensure that only actual goods delivered are included on the delivery receipts, and subsequent deliveries must be covered with different delivery receipts to reflect the actual flow of goods.  Also, ensure that these DRs are duly dated and the receipt of goods by the proper authority is clearly indicated on the space provided for;

Direct all suppliers to make deliveries to the Property/Supply Office who shall be accountable and liable for the receipt and inspection of the goods delivered; and

Develop and institute measures to address the lapses on the procurement procedure.

In view of the foregoing audit observations, we recommended that Management:
Strictly implement the provision of the guidelines above that no cash advances must be granted unless previously granted cash advances are settled first, in order to stop the accumulation of the unliquidated cash advances;
Stop the granting of cash advances without legally specific purposes and require that all request for cash advances are attached with the itemized budget or estimated expenses to detail the purpose to which these will be utilized;
Stop the granting of special purpose/time-bound cash advances to personnel who are not duly designated and duly bonded disbursing officer and limit their cash advances to their own traveling expenses only.  The same prohibition is applicable to elected officials of the Municipality, and this must be strictly imposed;
Always require the clearance from financial obligation from officials or employees separating from the service, through resignation or retirement, to ensure that their cash advances are settled, either by submission of documents or through payment by deduction from whatever claim due them;
Conduct a meeting with the employees with unliquidated cash advances and remind them of their obligations to settle them as soon as possible.  Inform them that non-settlement thereof has equivalent charges and penalties as provided in the Civil Service Commission (CSC) Memorandum Circular (MC) No. 23, s. 2019;
Issue demand letters to the accountable officers with unliquidated cash advances amounting to P21,798,752.45, including those separated from the service and the DepEd teachers, and impose the necessary and applicable remedies or penalties to those who will not adhere to the demand letter, such as withholding of their salaries or any claims due them, to compel them to settle these cash advances;
Investigate the accounts aging with more than 10 years and make the necessary effort to demand the settlement or the refund thereof.  Based on the investigation conducted, if warranted, initiate the possibility of writing off these accounts; and
Lastly, require all the officers and employees, most specially the Department Heads and elected officials, to comply with the provisions of COA Circular 97-002 and other applicable rules and regulations, on the grant and utilization of cash advances to deter the unnecessary accumulation thereof, and to enable the Accounting Unit to present the expenses related thereof in the financial statements correctly and reliably.  Institute disciplinary measures to non-complying employees to enjoin them to abide the rules and regulations on the grant and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that the Municipal General Services Officer:
Submit on or before May 31, 2024 the RPCI and RPCPPE for CY 2023 by conducting actual physical count and incorporate therein the status of the properties noted during the actual physical count;
For the RPCI and RPCPPE of succeeding periods, require the General Services Officer (GSO) to conduct timely inventory of PPE and inventories and to coordinate with the Accounting Unit for reconciliation thereof, and to submit the complete and reconciled RCPPE and RPCI to the Office of the Auditor on or before the deadline of January 31 of the ensuing year;
Use all the prescribed forms set by the MNGAS for LGUs for reports, transparency, and accountability; and
Together with the Accounting Office, identify the unreconciled amount noted in CY 2022 which was carried over in 2023 balances and, if warranted, make the necessary adjustments either in the books of the Municipality or in the property records, to fairly present the balances of the PPEs in the financial statements.

We recommended that Management:
Make a proper representation thru a written request to the Source Agencies (SA) for authority to utilize the unused funds for projects or endeavors that are congruent to the PPAs of the SAs or to transfer the same to the General Fund so that these will be appropriated to accomplish the PPAs of the Municipality.  If such requests are disapproved, require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to facilitate the immediate return of the unutilized balances to the SAs or to the Bureau of Treasury (BTr), so that these will be used by the national government for social services or other PPAs of the government;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and process the return of the P500,000.00 PDAF so that these will be appropriated by the National Government for other notable PPAs;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to return the unutilized amount of P460,423.47 to the DILG if the purpose is already completed or no longer needed; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to review the entries made in the Due to NGAs account with regard to the fund given by the Provincial Local Government of Nueva Vizcaya and to draw the proper adjusting entries to reclassify the accounts correctly, pursuant to COA Circular 2015-009.

We recommended that the Management:
Require all the personnel to settle all the unliquidated cash advances and refund any unutilized balances, so that these will be available for use;
Issue demand letter to the Construction Company in order to collect the amount of 183,809.83;
Require both the Accounting and Treasury office to reconcile the Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds Accounts and immediately transfer the net amount of P1,253,843.80 to the Trust Fund and make the necessary entries in the books to settle the accounts; and
Stop the practice of juggling of funds so that the cash availability of each funds is guaranteed and the proper implementation of the PPAs corresponding each funds will not be adversely affected.

We recommended that Management:
Expedite the completion of the partially completed 2023 and prior years’ development projects;
Realign or reprogram the current year savings of 2023 and those of prior years for development PPAs, so that these will not remain idle, and their money value will translate into the betterment of the lives of the people of Alfonso Castañeda;
Evaluate the unimplemented projects if these are still necessary, appropriate, or incidental to efficient and effective local governance, and those which are essential to the promotion of the general welfare of the people, as well as if these are procurement-and-implementation-ready, otherwise, realign or reprogram the funds to other priority development PPAs that can be implemented immediately;
the implementation of these projects under the 20% development funds are in line with the provisions of DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1, s. 2020; and
submit the accomplishment report for CY 2023 and the detailed SAAOB for Development Fund on or before May 15, 2024.

Hasten the reprogramming of the savings from prior years’ implementation so that these will be implemented in the succeeding year and will result in the immediate prevention or mitigation of adverse effects of disasters that may befall in the Municipality;
Review the planned activities or projects under the continuing appropriation, implement if these are still warranted, so that the funds will not become idle.  Otherwise, realign the funds to more notable and priority PPAs of MDRRM Office;
Continue to improve the utilization of the MDRRM funds and to comply with the provisions of RA No. 10121. Ensure that disbursements were all aligned with the Investment Plan; and
MDRRM, Accounting and Budget Office coordinate as to the implementation, appropriation and recording to identify the exact amount and projects that were implemented in order to generate a more reliable data to be used in decision making for reprogramming, abandonment and assessing the priority projects.

We recommended that Management should:
Instruct all the concerned personnel to ensure that all dates and other necessary information required in the various documentary requirements attached to the procurement of various goods must be filled out properly, completely and truthfully to ascertain compliance to applicable procedures, rules and regulations;
Inform the heads of the agencies and other concerned personnel that approval of POs must be made by the appropriate approving official of the Municipality in order that contracts entered into with the Suppliers are valid and effective;
Instruct the GSO to include the name of the canvassers in the RFQ to clearly establish their accountability as to the veracity of the canvass of prices or request for quotations made;
Inform the Suppliers and all the government employees of the Municipality that goods must be delivered directly to the GSO Office, to be duly accepted by them and inspected by the authorized inspector, before these are released to the end-users who will accept the goods through the RIS form; Ensure that the procedure of acquisition, requisition and issuance of goods are followed religiously;
Require the accounting unit and treasury unit to ensure that documentary requirements are all present and completely filled out before payments for these are processed and released, in compliance with Section 4 of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1445; and
Take measures to promote transparency and accountability in the management of public finances pursuant to Article 9, Chapter II of the United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC).

We recommended that the Management:
Properly fill out the supporting documents so that these will serve their very purpose and for transparency purposes;
Designate appropriate personnel who should conduct pre- and post- inspection repairs to be more effective in addressing the needs of repair and maintenance, not just for motor vehicles, but all the PPEs of the agency;
Require the preparation of repair history and obtain warranty certificates from suppliers or repair and maintenance service providers in compliance with the requirements for the Repairs and Maintenance of Machinery and Equipment set forth under COA Circular No. 2023-004;
Attach also before and after picture, if applicable, to document the repairs made;
Require the lacking documents indicated above, particularly the ORs or invoices or any proof of payments made to the Supplier to support the disbursements made; and
Instruct the Accounting and Treasury office to ensure that documentary requirements for repairs and maintenance are strictly adhered to before processing and release of any disbursements relative thereto.

We recommended that Management require:
The Contractors of the previous and newly constructed projects to submit the as-built plans for recording, safekeeping and future references;
All concerned personnel to comply with the documentary requirements prescribed by COA Circular 2023-004, particularly for the disbursement of progress and final payments of various projects of the Municipality to ensure the transaparency and compliance with rules and regulations of the transactions;
The Municipal Accountant  and Municipal Treasurer to vigilantly ensure that the documentary requirements of the DVs are complete and proper before these are processed, approved, and paid to claimants; and
The responsible offices and personnel for the aforementioned documentary deficiencies to submit to COA Office, if available and possible, in compliance with the aforementioned rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Management:
Fill the vacancies which are provided with budget with qualified individuals by following the process of recruitment to reduce the list of job orders that are doing regular agency functions and to reduce also the charges in the maintenance and other operating expenses which could be used for other social services of the LGU. This will boost their morale and they may enjoy the benefits of a regular employee. Without regular hiring, continuous separation of employees due to retirement, dismissal, resignation and death, and new created positions, vacant positions will accumulate which affects the services of the Municipality;
Design policies or procedures that will maximize the services of both the permanent and non-permanent personnel involved in the administrative, clerical, driver, liaison, security, and utility workers, such as assignment of multi-tasks to personnel (dual functions or serving two or more offices), centralizing personnel that provides janitorial services or centralizing procurement activities to GSO in line with appropriate rules and regulations;
Stop engaging the services of excessive and unnecessary JOs, otherwise, payment of their wages will be disallowed in audit;
Instruct the HRMO to:
Evaluate the accomplishments of each administrative, clerical, driver, liaison, security, and utility workers to identify duplication or redundant responsibilities, particularly those assigned in the Office of the Municipal Mayor, Office of the Municipal Vice Mayor, and Office of the Sangguniang Bayan, and to immediately recommend the termination of the contracts, if warranted, to avoid incurrence of unnecessary expenditures.  At the same time, asses the needs of administrative, clerical, liaison and utility of each office and designate a reasonable number of non-permanent personnel to complement the existing permanent personnel to deliver effective and efficient services; and
Assess the existing organizational structure of the Municipality, taking into consideration the service requirements and financial capability thereof, to reduce the hiring of JO personnel.

We recommended that the Management:
formulate guidelines for the conduct of LGU’s Team Building activities, using as reference the CSC Resolution No. 101262 dated June 22, 2010 and COA Resolution No. 2012-014 dated November 15, 2012 or those of other government agencies, in order to achieve their objectives and have a smooth, orderly and economical team building activity. Ensure that the guidelines are in place before the conduct of another TBA to ascertain adherence to rules and regulations;
Address the documentary requirements deficiencies noted above and require the submission of the lacking documents and explanations from concerned personnel, if necessary, and submit the same to COA Office;
Stop the conduct of TBAs if these are not appropriately budgeted. Future TBAs must be appropriated using the proper accounts and charge the same for the cost incurred in the conduct thereof, in consonance with applicable accounting and budgeting rules and regulations; and
Ensure that the conduct of TBA are done in a manner that motivates and capacitates all the employees of the Municipality and not just for selected few offices or employees.

